April 1345","1442":"1442","1385":"1385","1341":"1341","Abt 1401":"about 1401","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","La Mote, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England":"Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Godard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Reynald, Alcide, Armand, Aurel, Celine, Cyprien, Dominique, Emile, Etienne, Euclide, Gilles.","French: from the personal name <i>Godard</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Goddard  ).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Goddard  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Godar","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Gaudard</b>: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Waldhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule, power’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’, or a variant of   Godard  .","French (northern): variant of <b>Godart</b>, itself a variant of   Godard  ."]},{"name":"Goddard","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Godhard</i>, a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The name was popular in Europe during the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Saint Gotthard, an 11th-century bishop of Hildesheim who founded a hospice on the pass from Switzerland to Italy that bears his name. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","English: perhaps occasionally a variant of the occupational name   Gothard  . The two surnames may have been much confused.","French: variant of   Godard  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":36,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel Godard was born on 5 April 1345, in Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England. She married Sir John Wydeville in 1380, in Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1401, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"5 April 1345–Abt 1401":"5. aprill 1345–umbes 1401","1341–1401":"1341–1401","–Male":"Surnud","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1345–1401":"1345–1401","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","5 April 1345":"5. aprill 1345","1442":"1442","1385":"1385","1341":"1341","Abt 1401":"umbes 1401","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","La Mote, Maidstone, Kent, England":"Maidstone, Kent, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England":"Swanbourne, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"5 April 1345–Abt 1401":"5. huhtikuuta 1345–noin 1401","1341–1401":"1341–1401","–Male":"Kuollut","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1345–1401":"1345–1401","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","5 April 1345":"5. huhtikuuta 1345","1442":"1442","1385":"1385","1341":"1341","Abt 1401":"noin 1401","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","La Mote, Maidston